        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "AI Preference Labeling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "AI preference labeling is the process of using a large language model to generate (chosen, rejected) preference pairs at scale, replacing human annotators. Unlike the self-critique loop which compares an original response to its constitutional revision, preference labeling compares two independently generated responses and assigns a winner."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "AI preference labeling pipeline: sample responses, pair them, judge with LLM, filter low-confidence and ties, output preference dataset"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Five-Step Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Sample"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Generate N responses per prompt from the SFT model at temperature 0.7-0.9, giving response diversity."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Pair"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Create "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "inlineMath",
                    "attrs": {
                      "latex": "\\binom{N}{2}"
                    }
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " pairs per prompt. For N=4, this is 6 pairs — or random-sample if N is large."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Judge"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": An LLM judge compares each pair and outputs a preference. Position is randomised and the result is debiased by swapping."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Filter"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Discard ties and low-confidence judgements (logprob confidence below threshold "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "inlineMath",
                    "attrs": {
                      "latex": "\\tau"
                    }
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ")."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Dataset"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Output a (prompt, chosen, rejected) dataset for downstream DPO or reward model training."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Judge Prompt Design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The judge prompt has three key elements:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Dimension"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Specify the evaluation axis (helpfulness, harmlessness, honesty, instruction-following). Explicit dimensions reduce ambiguity and verbosity bias compared to a bare 'which is better' prompt."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Anti-length bias instruction"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Include 'do not prefer a response simply because it is longer' in the system prompt."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Hard output constraint"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Ask for exactly one letter (A or B) as the final output to enable logprob extraction."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "JUDGE_SYSTEM = (\n    \"You are an expert AI evaluator. Your task is to judge the quality of two\"\n    \" responses to the same prompt. Focus on: {dimension}.\\n\"\n    \"Do NOT prefer a response simply because it is longer. Judge quality, not length.\\n\"\n    \"Answer with only the letter A or B.\"\n)\n\nJUDGE_USER = (\n    \"Prompt: {prompt}\\n\\n\"\n    \"Response A:\\n{response_a}\\n\\n\"\n    \"Response B:\\n{response_b}\\n\\n\"\n    \"Which response better satisfies the prompt given the dimension {dimension}?\"\n)\n\nDIMENSIONS = [\"helpfulness\", \"harmlessness\", \"honesty\", \"instruction-following\"]\n\ndef judge_pair(\n    client, prompt: str, response_a: str, response_b: str,\n    dimension: str = None, model: str = 'gpt-4o',\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns dict with 'label' ('A', 'B', or 'tie') and 'confidence' (0-1).\n    Debiases by swapping positions and requiring agreement.\n    \"\"\"\n    import random\n    if dimension is None:\n        dimension = random.choice(DIMENSIONS)\n\n    def single_call(r_a, r_b):\n        resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model=model,\n            messages=[\n                {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": JUDGE_SYSTEM.format(dimension=dimension)},\n                {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": JUDGE_USER.format(\n                    prompt=prompt, response_a=r_a, response_b=r_b,\n                    dimension=dimension\n                )},\n            ],\n            max_tokens=1,\n            temperature=0,\n            logprobs=True,\n            top_logprobs=2,\n        )\n        choice = resp.choices[0]\n        label = choice.message.content.strip().upper()\n        # Extract confidence from logprobs\n        import math\n        top = choice.logprobs.content[0].top_logprobs\n        probs = {t.token.strip().upper(): math.exp(t.logprob) for t in top}\n        conf = probs.get(label, 0.5)\n        return label, conf\n\n    label1, conf1 = single_call(response_a, response_b)\n    label2, conf2 = single_call(response_b, response_a)\n    # Remap label2 back to original A/B labelling\n    mapped2 = \"A\" if label2 == \"B\" else \"B\"\n\n    if label1 == mapped2:\n        return {'label': label1, 'confidence': (conf1 + conf2) / 2}\n    return {'label': 'tie', 'confidence': 0.5}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Batch Labeling with Confidence Filtering"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom datasets import Dataset\n\nasync def label_dataset_async(\n    client,\n    prompts: list[str],\n    responses_a: list[str],\n    responses_b: list[str],\n    confidence_threshold: float = 0.7,\n    max_concurrent: int = 50,\n) -> Dataset:\n    \"\"\"Label pairs with debiased AI judge; filter low-confidence and ties.\"\"\"\n    sem = asyncio.Semaphore(max_concurrent)\n\n    async def label_one(i):\n        async with sem:\n            result = judge_pair(\n                client, prompts[i], responses_a[i], responses_b[i]\n            )\n            return i, result\n\n    labels = await asyncio.gather(*[label_one(i) for i in range(len(prompts))])\n\n    chosen, rejected, kept_prompts = [], [], []\n    for i, result in sorted(labels):\n        if result[\"label\"] == \"tie\":\n            continue\n        if result[\"confidence\"] < confidence_threshold:\n            continue\n        if result[\"label\"] == \"A\":\n            chosen.append(responses_a[i])\n            rejected.append(responses_b[i])\n        else:\n            chosen.append(responses_b[i])\n            rejected.append(responses_a[i])\n        kept_prompts.append(prompts[i])\n\n    print(f\"Kept {len(chosen)}/{len(prompts)} pairs after filtering\")\n    return Dataset.from_dict({\n        \"prompt\": kept_prompts,\n        \"chosen\": chosen,\n        \"rejected\": rejected,\n    })"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The confidence threshold "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "\\tau"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " controls the quality-quantity tradeoff. At "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "tau=0.7"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", roughly 30-40 % of pairs are discarded. Empirically, keeping only high-confidence pairs ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "tau >= 0.8"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") improves DPO downstream performance by 5-10 % on helpfulness benchmarks at the cost of 40-60 % fewer training examples."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-Dimensional Judgment"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Different dimensions of quality can conflict: a more helpful response may be less safe. Multi-dimensional judging exposes this tension and allows dimension-specific reward models:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def multi_dimensional_judge(\n    client, prompt: str, response_a: str, response_b: str,\n    dimensions: list = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Judge on multiple dimensions, return per-dimension results.\n    Useful for diagnosing which dimensions drive most disagreements.\n    \"\"\"\n    if dimensions is None:\n        dimensions = DIMENSIONS\n    results = {}\n    votes = {'A': 0, 'B': 0, 'tie': 0}\n    for dim in dimensions:\n        r = judge_pair(client, prompt, response_a, response_b, dimension=dim)\n        results[dim] = r\n        votes[r[\"label\"]] += 1\n    # Majority vote across dimensions\n    winner = max(('A', 'B'), key=lambda x: votes[x])\n    if votes[winner] <= len(dimensions) // 2:\n        winner = \"tie\"\n    return {'per_dimension': results, 'aggregate': winner, 'votes': votes}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pairs where dimensions disagree (e.g., A wins on helpfulness but B wins on harmlessness) are valuable for training dimension-conditional reward models. They are also natural candidates for human spot-checking to verify where the AI judge diverges across dimensions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Confidence via Log-Probabilities"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the judge API supports log-probability output (OpenAI, Anthropic, Together), extract the confidence from the logit at the answer token:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{confidence} = \\sigma(\\log P(\\text{A}) - \\log P(\\text{B}))"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This normalised score is calibrated in the Bradley-Terry sense: a confidence of 0.9 means the judge is 9x more likely to say A than B. Pairs with confidence near 0.5 are essentially coin flips and should be discarded."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Auditing Label Quality Against Human Judgement"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def audit_label_quality(\n    ai_labels: list[str],\n    human_labels: list[str],\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Compute agreement stats between AI and human labels.\"\"\"\n    assert len(ai_labels) == len(human_labels)\n    n = len(ai_labels)\n    # Filter ties from both sides for agreement computation\n    pairs = [\n        (a, h) for a, h in zip(ai_labels, human_labels)\n        if a != \"tie\" and h != \"tie\"\n    ]\n    if not pairs:\n        return {'error': 'no non-tie pairs'}\n    agree = sum(1 for a, h in pairs if a == h)\n    agreement = agree / len(pairs)\n\n    # Compute Cohen's kappa\n    from sklearn.metrics import cohen_kappa_score\n    ai_filtered = [a for a, h in pairs]\n    hu_filtered = [h for a, h in pairs]\n    kappa = cohen_kappa_score(ai_filtered, hu_filtered)\n\n    return {\n        'n_pairs': n,\n        'n_non_tie': len(pairs),\n        'agreement': agreement,\n        'cohen_kappa': kappa,\n        'ai_tie_rate': ai_labels.count('tie') / n,\n    }\n\n# Healthy targets:\n# - agreement > 0.75  (75% of non-tie pairs match human)\n# - cohen_kappa > 0.4  (moderate agreement or better)\n# - ai_tie_rate < 0.2  (judge not too uncertain)"
          }
        ]
      },
